rounds.response:
My assessment after the first round  
- Value of my initial bundle: 23·5 + 22·8 + 11·12 + 20·29 + 10·33 = 1 281  
- Last offer (10 Wheat, 5 Wood → 2 Ore, 4 Brick) would have moved 50 + 40 = 90 value for 66 + 116 = 182 value – a 92-point net gain for me even at my own valuations – but it was turned down, which tells me Player 1 either over-val­ues Ore/Brick or under-values Wheat/Wood (relative to me).

New strategy  
1. I still want to convert low-per-unit-value Wheat (5) and Wood (8) into high-per-unit-value Ore (33) and Brick (29).  
2. To make the offer look sweeter, give Player 1 a positive quantity of *every* resource I ask for except Ore. My quantities are healthy, so I can afford to be slightly more generous.

New proposal  
I’ll offer to give away 12 Wheat + 4 Wood in exchange for 3 Ore + 2 Brick.  
Value I give up: 12·5 + 4·8 = 60 + 32 = 92  
Value I receive: 3·33 + 2·29 = 99 + 58 = 157  
Net gain ≈ 65 points, and the opponent receives 26 volume whereas I receive only 5 – leaving them with proportionally more “stuff”.

[Offer: 12 Wheat, 4 Wood -> 3 Ore, 2 Brick]
